The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting for long.
The fact that the Czech mobile operators are the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on it on Mobil.cz.
This was also confirmed by the ČTÚ Telecommunications Authority, which pointed out that the price for a text message is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in regulation of roaming fees, it is likely that a paradoxical situation will occur - for some customers of Czech mobile phone providers, text messages from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
Why is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100 %.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to blame the fact that there is an extremely high level of competition in the Czech market.
This is often due to the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who has often said in the past that there is no place for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of opportunities (by the way, it would probably hardly find any frequencies).
But there is still one possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile phone providers had to respond.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market in Great Britain, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don't have to look long for examples.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider succeeded in winning more than 100 thousand customers and thus becoming the country's five largest provider.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and text messages, but this is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be quite a good move to rely on a non-cliché target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar approach could be taken in the Czech Republic, as in Poland.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický's press spokesperson also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile phone providers think that they have no chance.
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile phone provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobileking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
It will be more likely to enter the market of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press spokesperson of the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do all they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile phone provider has long been demonstrated by the group GTS Novara, who wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the business sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve progress in negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl's press spokesperson.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has a great deal of specificity vis-à-vis other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says the statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Further suppliers point out the specificity of the Czech market.
The press spokesperson of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build further."
And she adds: "By the end of the year, a virtual provider will hardly appear in the T-Mobile network.
At this moment, we must already have a concrete offer to think so short-term."
Vodafone focuses his attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we consider to be the best from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to search for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, and another provider called more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull at a strand when it comes to something also proves the long round and round about the emergence of U:fon.
The strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ was at the time when U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
It is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately - unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It has exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem as his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile phone provider would be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile phone provider and a virtual provider about the hire of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers," said Kristián Chalupa, of the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS, in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not be surprising by representatives of the providers.
This is more than worrying by an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, ensuring that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreign, where virtual providers work normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the almost already moving harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions, is really shocking.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just like the absolutely same petrol price at the gas stations is certainly just chance and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not discovered in this case any signs of anti-competitive action, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so he does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for acting on the market.
The regulatory authority for telecommunications probably lacks the necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual providers," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary to enter the market of a virtual provider.
And the mobile phone provider - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if one does not go along with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the UOHS that three mobile phone providers are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Nova) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The shift from responsibility to responsibility for ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the UOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act, it has not been possible to enforce the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS only need to know this too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one's looking at it.
The operation of some pseudovirtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, is not taken into account.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
It is usually companies operating in the field of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually come only to the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding society," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be the case with those responsible for the mobile phone providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
In fact, from the activity of these companies, profits do not flow to them to be neglected, at the same time - unlike the actual virtual providers - they will not be affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone, so they cannot have it fully like the normal customers of the mobile phone providers."
But this alone would have to be at least strange for ČT.
In addition, another question arises for the UOHS.
Before such an approach, do mobile phone providers close their eyes, and why do they block themselves against a virtual provider?
It must be added that the UOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to be satisfied with the supplier's statement that they do not know anything about them and their terms and conditions would prohibit them.
When Czech Republic Is Not Most Expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual suppliers brought a marked decline in the price of the various services.
In all countries where virtual providers have been created, the classic providers have tried to prevent their development practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, the regulators intervened precisely at these moments, which in no way tried to safeguard the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are throwing the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we can't get rid of the impression that ambiguity in the competences in these cases is more than beneficial.
But let's not throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider will soon appear, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the UOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting (discriminatory) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will at last make no more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
