The Prague transport companies also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1st, 2008, will enter the history of Prague's transport operations as a date on which the first passengers will board an electronic coupon instead of a paper ticket in their pocket on a subway, tram or bus.
These can currently buy about a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or one-year coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and can also play it on their chip card at the information centres and branches of the transport operations at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobellisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons have been available on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used until the afternoon hours of more than four hundred customers.
Those who use the internet sale can really forget the output window at the subway stations where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon over the Internet, it is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, a switch with trained staff is also available to travellers, the interested party advises on the internet purchase and also plays the coupon on the card," says the spokesperson of the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be played on the opencards on self-service machines, which are mounted in some underground cities.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, reminding of ticket holders, the passengers may have noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but it should be eighty by the end of the year," Opatrný adds.
The coupon controls an automatic machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines that will work tomorrow is simple.
All you have to do is introduce the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon is self-contained.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants from the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia arrive in the capital.
"In the trains which are part of the Prague integrated traffic, the train attendants have readers to check the validity of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid. This organization compiles the timetables for the Prague transport operations.
The suburban buses have card readers at the cash desk at the driver's.
When entering, the chip card must not only be shown at the driver's side, but the open card must be placed at a marked place at the side of the cash desk.
In this way the driver controls the validity of the played coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons played, nothing is easier than to ask the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not drive by suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information on the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
