The drivers, who can fall back due to the alcohol level, will have to install the 'Alcolock'.
The authority orders that the driver who had three official penalties for the alcohol level be installed in his car of this system, which forbids him to start the car in drunk state. If he is alcoholic, then the car does not start.
The initiative was announced last month in June and is already part of the General Prosecutor's Office's report. According to its information, it is a pilot project that will last for a year.
The purpose is to re-socialise the driver, which gives him a course for the re-education of transport behaviour.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor's Office, experience, the Ministry of Transport and the Foundation of the Technical Institute for the Safety of Automobiles will also take part.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 % of drivers who were shown to be on alcohol-influenced driving more than once were back on the tax.
The 'alcolock' would prevent this, because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the breathed air and prevents the start of the car when the driver has done alcohol testing; or if an alcohol concentration is determined which is higher than allowed.
It costs more than EUR 1 000, the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices already prevent up to 65% of the regulatory infringements in the first year following its introduction.
In Spain, it is expected that 115 lives could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it became a crime.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a legal reform can be implemented in the ordinary way, and yet a reform of the basic law is required, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The equipment is still available in the Spanish markets, in no business, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow because of the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which proposes to install this system in school buses, which has already been done in France.
