Doctrine - From the blood that got safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the most secure and efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves administered by the blood service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Canadian Government in February 1994 launched a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and to draw up guidelines to prevent a further disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to give his report, at that time several provinces set up a committee whose goal was to develop a new system for the administration of blood canning in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood-conservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
By the enormous efforts to improve the safety of the blood canned and by working in this area during the following years, we have regained public confidence," she says, before proudly stressing that in early 2008 almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that 'confidence is something extremely fragile'.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted in accordance with the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the presence of numerous cases of the human form of cattle insanity in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman who has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
And we didn't have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we called for one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease only progresses slowly, as it appears to be the case with the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was no doubt demonstrated that this disease was transmitted over the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we used has quite a meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable the virus to be detected directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibody against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation period that takes place between the time when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not see it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements allowed a significant reduction in the risk of transmission of AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people is in danger of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that you have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood canneds each year, it would take more than 24 years for a case in which HIV was transmitted via a blood container.
I believe that these days you can feel comfortable getting a blood transfusion or writing to restore health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year on the island of Réunion did the Chikungunya virus show up, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We have to monitor continuously," Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that besides a safe supply, Hema-Quebec also needs to provide sufficient supply.
The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
As cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which on average includes only 3% of Quebec's blood donation population.
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older who meets the fitness criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who supply their blood are not accepted, for example because they are suffering from AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
With this 3%, we are able to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and to get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that one rarely finds the time to spend an hour in blood donation,' says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec not only delivers blood cannings but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively for serious fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before they are stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, once considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood on stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
'A few weeks ago, we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand annually.
"We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year," explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
