The psychology of oversupply - or why we are willing to pay more
At auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the file bid.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even overly high prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play Lotto, while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
At both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the bark of the brain, was measured in the losers of the auction, in which the oversupply of the opponent plays an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-remuneration" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should participate against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group was also promised $15 reward in case they came out of the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was simply that the emphasis was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "lost" group were ready to use higher stakes than those in the control group or the "profit" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
They have so far only caused the behaviour observed at auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risks.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological methods, so that we now have a third explanation ready" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to see your doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated at a hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C and D can transmit the viruses through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, secretions or saliva).
Travelers are recommended to vaccination against viruses A and B, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A show up about two-three weeks after consumption of contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Then the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B, which causes far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected person is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and cancer of the liver.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen secretly destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have transfused blood before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the general doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Rightly recognized, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, thus preventing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, held in 2004 for the first time in patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this virus-inflammation of the chronic liver, its origin and the importance of early detection.
