Intelligent car imitates the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best method for developing new technologies to avoid accidents if not to imitate nature's obstacle sensors?
For example, the bees.
At the CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented that inspired the Nissan engineers of Hummelen in the creation of new accident-preventing systems.
In cooperation with the Tokyo University, Nissan has built the biomimetic system of type BR23C, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight each bee forms its own oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protective sign", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The compound eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identified obstacles before the BR23C in a field of vision of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision prevention process.
The obstacle is registered in second fractions, and the car robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver is purely instinctive.
"If it wasn't, the car robot wouldn't be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the Auto robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The entire process must reflect the behaviour of bees if they avoid other bees.
And that must be in the fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to the bees, it can be avoided, not up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, only towards the agility of the tyres.
While the bees here are infinitely open to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotational motion, or acceleration and brakes during the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy-efficient and therefore have a longer service life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it was the instinctive, intelligent response, and less the processing of the data, and even less the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process some inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It doesn't have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction based on previous maneuvers, so that it constantly uses only a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte heavy memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which, according to Nissan, will be standard production within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the goal.
