Napolitano: "Prevention against accidents at work is crucial"
Every day 2500 accidents at work occur in Italy, three people die and 27 remain unemployed for life.
For 2007, the Inail data (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were about 1200.
These figures prove the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as are caused by murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) in all the provinces of Italy will celebrate the 58th national day for the victims of accidents at work in order to draw the attention of social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The alarming data transmitted by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the question of prevention at work is," confirms the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to the prevention of jobs, to the protection of injured workers, to support the families of victims and to raise public awareness".
"An indignant "basta" has arisen; understandably in the case of tragedies, which, measured by their magnitude, cause some vertebrae in the media and public participation. But everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events, which can even repeat themselves in their own dynamics".
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely also a resource problem: education and information have to be invested decisively."
The many initiatives are of particular importance for a more direct awareness-raising in school frameworks by the young people who feed the world of work.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not distract from its social seriousness. We must put in place and improve a legislative standard.
On the one hand, the President of Gianfranco Fini stressed that "the phenomenon of labour-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency which insults the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work on decisive rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"The data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude the fact that the number of deaths due to work is far too high," says President Anmil, Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention. That's exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"How do you believe that you are basically doing too little to deal with the phenomenon of accidents? You can fight against it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli, but also stronger measures to inform workers who are already beginning in school."
"An additional effort is necessary - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers is required towards a phenomenon that constitutes a social emergency."
Mercandelli also spoke about "the progressive deterioration of the protection of the victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "absorbing of the social system against which we are fighting in recent years".
"The aim, therefore, is to give the worker a guarantee to insurance so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or random donations that are decided upon by a legislator from time to time."
Mp3 player in charge: risk of hearing damage
Loud music over a longer time span with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which in a report today published in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Csrseri (scientific committee on the current and recently identified health risks) of the EU.
"The report – as it says in a note – makes it clear that 5-10 % of those who, for at least five years, hear sound music with portable music instruments for more than one hour a day per week risk the permanent loss of their hearing."
"I'm worried that such a large number of young people who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones on a high volume will irrevocably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings – as it is said on the part of the Eu – there is a clear risk that leads to rapid action.
What really counts is to raise consumer awareness and make this information common.
In the light of these scientific findings, we need to re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology".
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"The scientists - as the EU Communication concludes - confirm that one is quite concerned and that the European Commission, together with the other members of the European Union and those concerned, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise that comes from portable music equipment and similar equipment."
There is already a European standard which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could come from too much noise.
One can greatly limit these damage in which one takes on solutions such as reducing the volume and the length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the European Scientific Committee points out that if the users of portable music instruments only listen to music (according to 89 decibels) five hours a week, so that the legal boundaries that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace have already been exceeded.
Those who cross this line of music risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This is therefore 5-10% of users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
