Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed in summer due to their refreshing quality and their vitamin wealth, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time with certain vital drugs, since they can have an extreme effect on the body’s intake.
David Bailey, professor of the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of packed as well as fresh fruit juices in combination with drug intake. During the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again called for an alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is sufficient to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to the extent that they are practically eliminated and thus endanger the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular medications, anxiolytic and neurological drugs, up to toxic levels.
MEDICAMENTS IN FAIR – The same Agency of the medicinal product in a report two years ago warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mixture, and stressed that it should be taken into account in combination with medicines such as diazepane or metadon.
IT IS NOT GRAPEFRUIT ONLY – according to the experts, orange juice and apple juice contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
The appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano, therefore: "Such results are usually transmitted immediately to the various international manufacturers who are free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is recommended that you always read the package leaflet and, if there is still any ambiguity, do not be afraid to ask a pharmacist or a doctor," says the expert at the Ansa Agency.
