The day of release of OpenOffice.org 3.0 has come; the Open Source software is gaining an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among free-lancers and public administration, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself to the public with some innovations: in addition to a revised and now more sparsely designed start-up menu, there is now finally a ground-breaking compatibility with Apple's Mac OS x operating system, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, which is the latest standard ISO version.
In addition, attention was paid to compatibility with Microsoft’s Office 2007, whose new formats (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx) can be read by OpenOffice.
Interesting are also some new features, such as those that allow to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which facilitates e.g. sending via e-mail. This includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphic graphic graphics modules and at the same time preserve the original appearance of the page.
Thus, "hybrid" PDF files can now be generated, which expand the typical graphics of Adobe format with the elements of a table and a word processing system.
Cooperation is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be processed by different users in a multi-hand manner, thus changing conflicts in the event of changes; in the case of the word processing system, a frabe is assigned to each processor in order to guarantee a better correction process.
Some companies are just about to publish various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result is to be made public in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download on the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. It follows the English version, which has been on the mirror since Friday.
Besides for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, you can send the installation CD to your home or office.
However, if freedom of movement can be an incentive for the dissemination of the programme in private households, it is also particularly in the field of business where OpenOffice could succeed: after all, various public administration and schools have already passed to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text-making program; Calc, the table-based program that aims to displace Excel; Impress, to create presentations such as PowerPoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of the more familiar access; and finally Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads – a goal that can easily be exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
