Students Victims of up to 900-Euro per room high rental prices
The market for apartments for students knows no crises.
According to the last study of the Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken very serious steps. Whole groups of students are losing their right to study, as their families are not able to support them at this level" – according to the Sunia responsible, Laura Mariani – "in these cities the great demand of the students leads to a deforming of the market, which has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most of the rental offers include a number of infringements: free contracts, missing registrations, no rent price limit, unauthorized subcontracting.
For the Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures, which lead to lower rent prices through a revision of taxation.
When considering the study more closely, it turns out that a bed in Milan is needed in the Brianza district about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Nere district) and ends with 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence, a bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where the students focus in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are for a sleeping place of needs, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, prices in the districts around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping place in a double room.
Only a little deeper are the rents in the neighbourhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those in outlying districts can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a sleeping place, for a room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari a bed costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they have a greater weight in the urban economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more common, such as Perugia, there is even another anomaly: a rental that is 25-30% higher than the average is required by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historical cinemas close because of the favored multiplex kinos.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This image of the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-salt complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the one-salt cinema in the center. A process that not only appears inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the traits of a cultural crime.
The most affected are historical places full of memories, "it is like losing a friend with whom one has covered a piece of street full of emotions," said the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oscar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It is about the history of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is lost forever.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: over the last five years, the enormous number of 316 traditional cinemas have been closed; these series paid mostly the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions include Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This is evidenced by the fact that the main culprits are the multiplex kinos, because they are precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: at 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy has led the lists, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, the president of Anec, "it is useful that new structures arise, but first of all the preservation of the already existing, because a hall in the city is closed, not all its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here the lack of budget for the trade association's fund remains clear: the debt burden recorded by the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
To preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros in the year would be necessary."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears surrounding the old cinemas, has decided to protect it by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy that aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures foreseen are tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in relation to local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at more affordable parking fees.
"It's a happy initiative," says Giuseppe Tornators, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also design new concepts.
But we certainly also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because finally the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that led me to establish the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had played with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have been living in Rome; when I pass the Rialto or Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside to avoid seeing the dust-covered posters.
