From a cut-off action in connection with the Dal Torrione case studies, the willingness to meet the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – making the public administration's actions identical to the interests of this clan."
When the energy emerges from the waves, suddenly the big ones run up
It is a non-defining money source that covers more than 70% of the planet's surface, and only now do these seem to understand the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and also looking for occupying, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the marine movements has been considered and examined for 70 years; these studies have not happened to be considerably intensified since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke down around 1980 the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pressing for new impetus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the global energy needs could be met by the ocean waves.
This would be equal to the double of the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides would be added.
Giants on the attack.
The first company that now relies on marine energy is Enersis, who has signed in 2005 a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies from the traditional energy industry that rely on marine energy extraction.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" – according to the spokesperson of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal – and weighs the opportunity to cooperate with us."
This is about the procurement of an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a sign that is not to be underestimated, especially when one considers that oil is still being mined by the US in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which invest in the new industry, are also not known about the details, so observers are talking about increasing interest.
Even better technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still under way, not least because the last doubts on the part of the environmentalists have not yet been resolved.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and also Scotland have a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected bows for example.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the bows up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The current is then sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this kind that are only waiting for the government's approval, and some of the energy obtained could also serve military facilities.
However, Verdant Power is already producing energy for a department store and a parklatz with the help of underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movement during the tide drives the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Extraction Research, a particular interest is immediately worth the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, sun exposure and also waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
It is tidal energy that led states like New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
